00:23:04,366 --> 00:23:09,033
If you say, oh, now I will fall in love into that lady or man, it's fake.

204
00:23:11,033 --> 00:23:21,766
It is a free decision, but as Schelling put it, a transcendental, a temporal free decision which you experience precisely as its opposite, as your fate.

205
00:23:22,733 --> 00:23:27,166
You experience love as, my God, I cannot escape it, I'm caught into it.

206
00:23:27,600 --> 00:23:28,433
And that's true freedom.

207
00:23:28,733 --> 00:23:29,766
That's the radical freedom.

208
00:23:30,133 --> 00:23:32,833
Now you will say, this is sentimental speculation.

209
00:23:33,400 --> 00:23:35,300
No, I'll use another example from my class.

210
00:23:35,433 --> 00:23:40,333
Isn't it exactly the same with a tough political decision?

211
00:23:40,833 --> 00:23:46,599
Not the simple decisions, vote for Macron, vote for Le Pen with Puff, I don't care.

212
00:23:47,533 --> 00:23:50,199
But let's make a pathetic example.

213
00:23:50,633 --> 00:23:57,233
There is war, my country is attacked, and I have to decide will I risk my life, do it or not.

214
00:23:58,133 --> 00:24:00,266
This is a free decision by me.

215
00:24:00,800 --> 00:24:07,433
But if you take the difficult decision that you will fight, you don't experience it as a choice.

216
00:24:08,100 --> 00:24:13,000
You experience it, I would love not to do it, but it's my duty, I cannot not do it.

217
00:24:13,833 --> 00:24:14,533
I have to do it.

218
00:24:15,733 --> 00:24:22,999
And I think this provides this wonderful dialectic described, as far as I know, by philosophy

219
00:24:23,700 --> 00:24:33,466
only nicely, clearly only by Hegel, how predestination is much more paradoxical if we read Protestantism

220
00:24:34,133 --> 00:24:40,866
in a materialist way than the simple notion, there is predestination, everything is decided no.

221
00:24:41,633 --> 00:24:48,666
means we have a faith, but we retroactively create this faith.

222
00:24:49,300 --> 00:24:56,233
Like I freely decide something and once I decide it, it retroactively becomes necessary.

223
00:24:56,933 --> 00:25:02,433
If I do the right thing, I experienced it my God, I couldn't do it otherwise, I had to do it.

224
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:03,633
That's freedom.

225
00:25:04,033 --> 00:25:07,033
So that's my first point about Protestantism.

226
00:25:07,666 --> 00:25:14,399
Which means that not only you are free, but you are even more free than you thought.

227
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:20,000
You are even responsible for your fate, for your necessity.

228
00:25:20,400 --> 00:25:34,000
And again, as I already explained in my classes, here psychoanalysis rejoins Protestantism.

229
00:25:34,300 --> 00:25:39,933
Because in psychoanalysis, the obvious result is something like predestination.

230
00:25:40,300 --> 00:25:50,633
You know, like, I think I'm a free being, but no, everything is predetermined through my past traumas, through whatever, you know, so I discover that I'm not free.

231
00:25:51,133 --> 00:25:56,566
And this was the fashionable lesson half a century ago with that fashion of structuralism in France.

232
00:25:57,033 --> 00:26:01,366
This is how psychoanalysis was read, structural psychoanalysis.

233
00:26:01,733 --> 00:26:09,199
You think you are a free subject, no. You are just a puppet, the big other, the symbolic order, runs the game, and so on.

234
00:26:09,833 --> 00:26:25,666
But look, Lacan follows here Freud, yes, you are over-determined, but you cannot use this over-determination or psychic necessity which makes you what you are.

235
00:26:26,133 --> 00:26:30,499
You cannot use it as an excuse, you know, like, to be vulgar, I'm sorry.

236
00:26:30,833 --> 00:26:35,566
I rape a child and then I say to the judges, sorry guys, what can I do?

237
00:26:35,733 --> 00:26:38,666
I was over determined by my unconscious complex.

238
00:26:39,100 --> 00:26:44,233
No, you are predestined by fate, but you are responsible even for that.

239
00:26:44,866 --> 00:26:47,933
You are much more radically responsible.

240
00:26:48,066 --> 00:26:57,999
And I can't go into it now, I already did it in my class to develop how the same goes also for, that's why it's a great thing, Kantian ethics.

241
00:26:58,433 --> 00:27:01,699
And Kant says, do Kant then do souls.

242
00:27:01,900 --> 00:27:03,633
You can do it because you must do it.

243
00:27:04,066 --> 00:27:08,166
Like no excuse to not do your duty.

244
00:27:08,400 --> 00:27:10,266
If it's your duty, you have to do it.

245
00:27:11,166 --> 00:27:15,166
But Kant, this is not so often noticed, goes even a step further.

246
00:27:15,733 --> 00:27:22,499
He also implies that even doing your duty cannot be an excuse for doing your duty.

247
00:27:23,033 --> 00:27:24,599
Like Chris, I hate you, let me do it.

248
00:27:25,100 --> 00:27:28,100
I have to do something, it's my duty which will hurt you.

249
00:27:28,933 --> 00:27:33,166
I don't have the right to tell you, sorry guy, but it's my duty.

250
00:27:33,433 --> 00:27:36,199
No, I don't have the right to externalize it.

251
00:27:36,500 --> 00:27:39,033
I'm not responsible only to do my duty.

252
00:27:39,433 --> 00:27:45,633
I have to fully subjectively assume also my duty in the sense of what is my duty.

253
00:27:46,700 --> 00:27:51,766
This is why incidentally, I mentioned this briefly in my class, and now I will stop with plagiarizing myself.

254
00:27:52,166 --> 00:27:54,199
Don't worry, I will not repeat my class.

255
00:27:54,933 --> 00:28:00,533
This is why I think that although I admire her, at some point in her otherwise wonderful

256
00:28:00,833 --> 00:28:05,699
Eichmann in Jerusalem, if I remember it correctly, Hannah Arendt was wrong.

257
00:28:06,466 --> 00:28:11,333
When she took seriously Eichmann's statement that she was just a good Kantian.

258
00:28:12,066 --> 00:28:19,366
He did his duty for him, duty was embodied in Führer's orders, so sorry I was doing my duty.

259
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:26,100
No, Eichmann did precisely the wrong thing.

260
00:28:26,333 --> 00:28:30,966
He was not a Kantian because he did something that Kant strictly prohibits.

261
00:28:31,533 --> 00:28:37,933
He used duty as an excuse, sorry, I kept killing millions of Jews, what can I do, that's my duty.

262
00:28:38,633 --> 00:28:45,099
No, you cannot refer to your duty as some objective determination that you have just to follow.

263
00:28:45,600 --> 00:28:48,666
You are radically responsible for your duties.

264
00:28:50,933 --> 00:28:53,966
Now I will complicate things.

265
00:28:55,700 --> 00:28:57,933
Now the end of self-pluggerizing.

266
00:28:58,033 --> 00:28:59,066
You will get some new stuff.

267
00:28:59,733 --> 00:29:06,199
This solution, this dialectical interconnection of necessity and freedom, where, yes, there is necessity,

268
00:29:06,833 --> 00:29:10,599
but this necessity is, in a deeper sense, contingent.

269
00:29:11,100 --> 00:29:13,533
Like, you do something in a contingent way.

270
00:29:14,400 --> 00:29:17,933
Once you do it, it retroactively becomes your fate.

271
00:29:18,833 --> 00:29:21,433
This solution works only on one condition.

272
00:29:22,100 --> 00:29:32,233
The subject, believer, agent, is absolutely constrained by the horizon of his or her finite subjectivity.

273
00:29:34,433 --> 00:29:41,866
What Protestantism prohibits is the very thought that as a believer, I can, as it were,

274
00:29:43,266 --> 00:29:52,833
took a position outside, above myself, and looked upon myself as a small particle in the vast reality.

275
00:29:53,533 --> 00:30:00,499
Here since I already mentioned Mao Zedong, I would like to criticize him a little bit

276
00:30:00,833 --> 00:30:07,799
at the philosophical level and incidentally because of some of my lines like this, Alain Badiou is even now mad at me, you know.

277
00:30:08,933 --> 00:30:21,066
Mao Zedong, I think, was wrong when he deployed his Olympic vision, reducing human experience to a tiny, unimportant cosmic detail.

278
00:30:21,500 --> 00:30:30,133
You know, in his famous statement where he say we don't fear atomic war and so on, okay, with that I in principle agree.

279
00:30:30,733 --> 00:30:40,566
But Mao went on and said this, a quote from Mao Zedong, the United States cannot annihilate the Chinese nation with its small stack of atom bombs.

280
00:30:41,566 --> 00:30:56,466
Even if the US atom bombs were so powerful that, when dropped on China, they would make a hole right through the earth, or even blew the earth up, that would hardly mean anything

281
00:30:56,833 --> 00:31:01,966
to the universe as a whole, though it might be a major event for the solar system.

282
00:31:03,200 --> 00:31:05,366
You know, it's kind of a weird excuse.

283
00:31:05,933 --> 00:31:11,599
OK, Americans can destroy us, but what does it mean from the standpoint of the universe or whatever?

284
00:31:14,900 --> 00:31:23,966
I think that this argument, Mao's, only works if in a pseudo-Kantian way.

285
00:31:24,400 --> 00:31:34,533
We presuppose, like, the problem is, where is Mao speaking from what subjective position when he states this.

286
00:31:35,100 --> 00:31:46,266
He acts as if he speaks from a totally external, purely divine position where you see objectively reality in human eyes, and then you can say,

287
00:31:46,700 --> 00:31:53,633
okay, our Earth is blown apart, fuck it, a tiny blimp in some small planet, who cares?

288
00:31:54,800 --> 00:32:00,166
But here I don't have time to develop it, but this is beautiful theological topic.

289
00:32:01,533 --> 00:32:12,533
Intelligent Protestantism have a wonderful vision where it's again that link between contingency and necessity.

290
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:17,233
On the one hand, yes, we are a tiny piece of feet in a vast universe.

291
00:32:19,333 --> 00:32:36,999
Protestantism is not ethnocentric, which is why Protestantism in so far as it stands for modernity was precisely the religious background of modern science, which precisely introduced the objective view of reality.

292
00:32:37,500 --> 00:32:43,500
You know that before Protestantism, the medieval world was earth in the center, although we

293
00:32:43,800 --> 00:32:56,166
humans were not the center of the universe, it was God, but nonetheless, we were the highest point of the created universe, everything turned around us, and so on and so on.

294
00:32:57,033 --> 00:33:05,299
So what Protestantism unites, I don't have time to develop it now just to give an idea, is I think something wonderful.

295
00:33:06,100 --> 00:33:09,233
At the same time, this extremely brutal view.

296
00:33:10,900 --> 00:33:13,266
From an inhuman gaze, we are nothing.

297
00:33:13,633 --> 00:33:16,766
A tiny species on Earth, it doesn't matter.

298
00:33:17,233 --> 00:33:26,933
But nonetheless, since we cannot ever really assume that view, external view, in our ethical practice,

299
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:41,700
we have to act as if whenever, and Kant puts it this very nicely, although objective science is telling us that fuck it, we are again one tiny piece of dust in the universe,

300
00:33:41,700 --> 00:33:55,666
Nonetheless, in a big ethical struggle, it's not just our fate that is decided, as it were, can't put it so nicely, the entire universe was created as a background for that struggle of ours.

301
00:33:56,133 --> 00:34:00,899
You know, I love this unity of extreme ethnocentrism.

302
00:34:01,700 --> 00:34:09,266
The world was created so that we can fight this battle, and this radically external view.

303
00:34:10,200 --> 00:34:17,733
Because this is, in a way, when you witness a big change, a revolution or whatever, even

304
00:34:18,366 --> 00:34:25,733
with Holocaust, I think the intelligent argument, even Habermas made it, who tries to be a rationalist,

305
00:34:26,733 --> 00:34:39,733
but Habermas, I don't agree with him, made once a nice point where he says that with Holocaust, and I would add nonetheless some other events, like what happened in Congo, other horrible things and so on.

306
00:34:40,600 --> 00:34:49,933
Something so horrible happens that you in a way diminish its horror when you reduce it to a simple human event.

307
00:34:50,900 --> 00:34:59,400
Something went wrong in class struggle, whatever, it's horrible to say Holocaust was just a sub-chapter in class struggle and effort and so on.

308
00:35:00,300 --> 00:35:15,100
Something that Habermas says very intelligently that theological dimension means here just a way, a specific way, to signal that something so horrible happened that it doesn't fit our universe.

309
00:35:16,166 --> 00:35:23,166
We cannot, I'll put it this way, we cannot simply renormalize it as just another historical event.

310
00:35:23,933 --> 00:35:42,333
That's why, isn't this the title, you may correct me, maybe you know it more, of one of the books on Holocaust, The Black Sun, the sun itself turned out, you know, like Like as some people say nicely, when something like Holocaust happened, it's a shame that the world continued to exist.

311
00:35:42,733 --> 00:35:48,799
If there were to be an elementary ethic in the world, out of shame the world should have fallen apart.

312
00:35:50,133 --> 00:35:58,699
So that's, and now comes, I thank you for your patience, maybe my first more interesting aspect.

313
00:36:00,633 --> 00:36:06,166
It's part of this, that's the paradox of Protestantism, radically anthropocentric,

314
00:36:06,633 --> 00:36:10,766
but at the same time let's look at ourselves with inhuman eyes.

315
00:36:11,933 --> 00:36:22,899
Here I think, but I'm reading them, by them I mean assemblage theory, new materialism, object-oriented ontology, they can be combined with my position.

316
00:36:23,633 --> 00:36:32,699
Because what's the true, let's call it naively, shattering ethical greatness, although I read it in a different way that it's usually read off.

317
00:36:33,133 --> 00:36:46,866
I will focus here on so-called new materialism, Jane Bennett, this idea that we should look at our life in the middle of nature as an interaction of agents.

318
00:36:48,066 --> 00:37:02,999
She calls them, I think, following Latour actants, and they interact and we should look at it through an inhuman gaze, to see this as a process of interaction, living interaction,

319
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:05,533
we are just one of the elements.

320
00:37:06,233 --> 00:37:15,099
In her book, I think, Vibrant Matter, Jane Bennett provides a beautiful description of a trash site.

321
00:37:15,833 --> 00:37:19,966
She said, we think trash side just nothing, piece of sheet there, things rotting.

322
00:37:20,800 --> 00:37:27,200
But she says, what if we look at it with an imagined inhuman eye as a living process?

323
00:37:27,533 --> 00:37:43,833
We have a complex interaction of rotting trash, worms, insects, abandoned machines, chemical poisons, and each place, each element, actant, plays its own never purely passive role.

324
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:55,666
I think, so-called new materialism or object-oriented ontology at its most radical, to provide this type of inhuman view.

325
00:37:57,333 --> 00:38:03,099
And again, I think there is an authentic theoretical and ethico-political insight in such an approach.

326
00:38:08,933 --> 00:38:21,899
Society thereby becomes a social phenomenon, but the limits of sociality are expanded to include all material bodies participating in the relevant assemblage.

327
00:38:22,466 --> 00:38:34,333
Say, an ecological public is a group of bodies, some humans, most of them not, and they are subjected to harm defined as a diminished capacity for action.

328
00:38:35,500 --> 00:38:50,966
Of course, the ethical implication is that we have to acknowledge the entanglement within a larger assemblage, like we are not, nature doesn't serve us, we are just one among the agents on the earth.

329
00:38:52,200 --> 00:38:55,966
Here comes my first modest disagreement.

330
00:38:57,500 --> 00:39:04,600
I think unknowingly this argument of her description also remains radically anthropocentric.

331
00:39:04,833 --> 00:39:23,799
know in what sense, the more it tries to be objective at the level of content, the more it privileges us, human species, as the only species which has access to this universality.

332
00:39:24,333 --> 00:39:40,166
That's my problem with those so-called deep ecologists who claim animals, even a Scandinavian friend of mine, wrote a book where he claims even beautiful canyons, pieces of nature,

333
00:39:40,800 --> 00:39:54,566
should be treated as subject agents with human rights, like there is a beautiful organic totality in, he gives a beautiful example of wonderful rock formation in Iceland,

334
00:39:54,633 --> 00:40:06,533
and he says not only, as it's popular to say now, animals should have their rights, not just human rights, priests should have their rights, even rivers should have their rights.

335
00:40:06,566 --> 00:40:07,533
But you know what's the catch?

336
00:40:08,433 --> 00:40:09,166
They don't know it.

337
00:40:09,633 --> 00:40:18,366
We automatically, when we want to act as deep ecologists, is the most arrogant, anthropocentric position that you can imagine.

338
00:40:19,100 --> 00:40:25,066
Because you automatically assume that we, yes, we apparently humiliate ourselves.

339
00:40:25,766 --> 00:40:33,166
But we humans are the only agents who know, who have access to this universal dimension.

340
00:40:33,600 --> 00:40:36,266
I mean, trees don't know about their rights.

341
00:40:36,600 --> 00:40:43,133
When a river is ruining the trees, it doesn't know that it is infringing upon others' rights.

342
00:40:43,733 --> 00:40:58,033
You know, it's the same falsity as the one, I think, of a certain type of multiculturalism where we claim that we are not the only ones who have the right.

343
00:40:58,500 --> 00:41:00,833
Also, other cultures have the right.

344
00:41:01,333 --> 00:41:06,499
But the more we humiliate ourselves of Western civilization, we are just one among them,

345
00:41:07,200 --> 00:41:17,900
the more we act as the only one who has the access to the universal dimension and can say what the rights of the other such.

346
00:41:18,866 --> 00:41:22,599
I felt this quite often in debates in the United States,

347
00:41:23,300 --> 00:41:29,966
its typical arrogant, politically correct attitude, that, and once I witnessed it,

348
00:41:30,600 --> 00:41:35,766
a white liberal guy, of course they're always white, defended black rights.

349
00:41:36,033 --> 00:41:38,199
That's perfect, I'm radically for them.

350
00:41:39,100 --> 00:41:42,733
But the problems were what that some black guys then didn't agree with him.

